social practice that through time takes on the normative power of law-acquired local meaning and changed over time. Yannakakis analyzes sources ranging from missionary and Inquisition records to Native pictorial histories, royal surveys, and Spanish and Native-language court and notarial documents. By encompassing historical actors who have been traditionally marginalized from legal histories and highlighting spaces outside the courts like Native communities, parishes, and missionary schools, she shows how imperial legal orders were not just imposed from above but also built on the ground through translation and implementation of legal concepts and procedures. Yannakakis argues that, ultimately, Indigenous claims to custom, which on the surface aimed to conserve the past, provided a means to contend with historical change and produce new rights for the future.  afunded by Emory University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCustomary law courtszMexicoxHistory. 0aIndians of MexicoxLegal status, laws, etcxHistory. 0aIndians of MexicoxPolitics and government. 0aJustice, Administration ofzMexicoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh2 aEmory Universityefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478093572?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478093572zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478093572/original  a978-3-11-099775-0 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA